# sshd configuration for the openhost-sftp container.
#
# This sshd serves SFTP only — no shell access, no agent forwarding,
# no port forwarding.  The single user "owner" is chrooted to a
# data directory and authenticates exclusively with SSH public keys.
#
# Hardening choices, all deliberate:
#
#   * PasswordAuthentication no: SSH keys only.  We never want a
#     password-auth surface on the public internet.
#   * PermitRootLogin no: even if "root" had keys configured
#     somehow, they wouldn't work.
#   * AllowUsers owner: only the one user we created can connect.
#   * Match User owner / ForceCommand internal-sftp: even if
#     someone tries to launch a shell on a successful auth, we
#     replace their command with the in-process SFTP server.
#   * ChrootDirectory: confines the owner to one dir on the
#     filesystem.
#   * AllowTcpForwarding no, X11Forwarding no, AllowStreamLocalForwarding no,
#     PermitTunnel no: kill every "could this be (ab)used as a
#     tunnel" feature.

# -- network -------------------------------------------------------
Port 22
ListenAddress 0.0.0.0
AddressFamily any

# -- logging -------------------------------------------------------
LogLevel INFO
SyslogFacility AUTH

# -- protocol ------------------------------------------------------
Protocol 2

# -- host keys -----------------------------------------------------
# Generated by start.sh on first boot into $OPENHOST_APP_DATA_DIR
# so the host identity persists across container rebuilds.  The
# paths below are placeholders; start.sh substitutes
# ``__PERSIST__`` with the actual $OPENHOST_APP_DATA_DIR value at
# container start (compute_space mounts that dir at
# /data/app_data/<app-name>/, NOT /data, so we can't hardcode an
# absolute path here).  The keys live outside /etc/ssh because
# that path is overlay'd by the image and would not survive a
# rebuild.
HostKey __PERSIST__/sshd-host-keys/ssh_host_ed25519_key
HostKey __PERSIST__/sshd-host-keys/ssh_host_rsa_key

# -- auth ---------------------------------------------------------
PasswordAuthentication no
KbdInteractiveAuthentication no
PermitEmptyPasswords no
ChallengeResponseAuthentication no
PubkeyAuthentication yes
PermitRootLogin no
AuthorizedKeysFile __PERSIST__/authorized_keys
AllowUsers owner

# -- session ------------------------------------------------------
#
# We allow interactive shells and arbitrary command execution via
# SSH for the ``owner`` user (no ``PermitTTY no``, no
# ``ForceCommand``, no ``ChrootDirectory``).  This makes the
# container a general-purpose SSH endpoint rather than a strict
# SFTP-only one — operators can ``ssh owner@host`` to debug,
# ``ssh owner@host <command>`` for one-off remote commands,
# rsync/sftp/scp/rclone for file transfer, and so on.
#
# Trade-off: anyone with a private key matching an entry in
# authorized_keys gets shell access inside the container.  The
# blast radius is bounded by the container's own isolation —
# OpenHost's --cap-drop=ALL plus a tight default capability set
# means this is not equivalent to root on the host.  An attacker
# with a key can read/write the SFTP files dir, edit
# authorized_keys (bypassing the SSO-gated frontend), and run
# any binary the image ships.  They cannot escape the container,
# read other apps' data, or affect the host.  If you want to
# tighten this back to strict SFTP-only, re-add ``PermitTTY no``
# and the ``Match User owner`` block with ``ForceCommand
# internal-sftp`` + ``ChrootDirectory``.
#
# We keep the forwarding restrictions because they're useful
# even with shell access enabled — a stolen key shouldn't be
# able to use the container as a SOCKS proxy or X11 hop.
AllowTcpForwarding no
X11Forwarding no
AllowStreamLocalForwarding no
PermitTunnel no
GatewayPorts no
ClientAliveInterval 60
ClientAliveCountMax 3

# -- subsystem ----------------------------------------------------
# Use sshd's built-in SFTP subsystem rather than spawning a
# separate sftp-server binary.  The path to the binary is
# distribution-dependent; "internal-sftp" lives inside sshd
# itself, which is more portable across base images.  Without
# the chroot directive (now removed), SFTP sessions land in the
# owner's home directory like ssh sessions do.
Subsystem sftp internal-sftp
